    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. So it's basically just a byproduct of the energy process. But why does it feel so much like an actual physical irritation or something 'attacking' the muscle during the set? It feels much more intrusive than just a normal chemical change.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The sensation of burning you're feeling is actually your muscles' way of signaling that they're under stress, trying to warn you not to push too hard too fast. This discomfort might seem like a direct attack, but it's actually your body's intuitive response to the lactic acid buildup. As lactic acid levels rise, they can cause a decrease in pH within your muscle cells, leading to a temporary reduction in the efficiency of muscle contractions. This sensation is a protective mechanism, letting you know when you're nearing your limits. It's not an actual physical attack; it's more like your muscles are trying to communicate with you to help prevent overexertion and possible injury.",
      "source": "target",
